Title: The Ancient Magus' Bride, Vol. 16
Author: Kore Yamazaki
My Review:
From all the volumes regarding the College, this one is my favourite so far; I'm inclined to believe this is due to the inclusion of small segments with Chise's and Elias' adventures in their country side house which is a lovely contrast to the lack of Chise-Elias interaction focus present during the College Arch.
I truly enjoyed the character development present in this volume, a strong must have in comparison to the previous volumes where I felt a slow paced world and background building seemed to swallow the narrative.
This volume has one of my favourite quotes so far: "the rain hides away the smell of the sun".

Title: Dark Asylum (Jem Flockhart, #2)
Author: E.S. Thomson
My Review:
I know not where to begin reviewing this masterpiece. Such thrilling paragraphs, engaging story line, mindblowing character development!

This book froze the blood in my veins, crushed my heart, threw me in a rollercoaster of emotional despair and fear for my beloved characters.

When I thought I had figured out who the murderer was, Thomson strikes again with her exceptional reasoning and shocking plot twists.
I avidly recommend this book to lovers of the crime genre, Victorian settings, apothecary aesthetics and the intricate knowledge of herbs and poisons!

***
I would like to leave you with the following quote which, in my humble opinion, defines the astonishing levels of emotion this book contains:

«"I had to protect her. I said I would. I would not have her sent back to the gallows. (...)"
"And she never knew who you were?"
Thank God she did not. But I had to protect her. I said I would."»

Title: Howl’s Moving Castle (Howl’s Moving Castle, #1)
Author: Diana Wynne Jones
My Review:
I was introduced to Jones' fantasy through Ghibli's Howl's Moving Castle movie at a young age. I grew you wishing to get my own moving castle and my own fire demon.
It took me years to realise the movie was based on a book, so off I went to find myself a copy.
I must confess, I am quite biased when it comes to Howl's Moving Castle so this review should be taken with a pinch of salt:
Sophie, Howl and Michael made me laugh uncontrollably, the Witch gave me the scare of my life, Miss Pentstemmon made me want to hug my heart and Calcifer... well, Calcifer is a dream of a demon I'd love to befriend.
The story is medium paced, told in a "show, don't tell" fashion that drags you into the book. World building is intricate and complex, which compels me to read more of Jones' book.
Howl's Moving Castle took me on an amazing adventure across the lands of Ingary, and the gods know I will be rereading this book for eternity.

Title: 魔法使いの嫁 15 (Mahōtsukai no yome, #15)
Author: Kore Yamazaki
My Review:
As usual, it is a pleasure to delve into the magical work of the College. Although I do personally find Chise and Elias' adventures in the cottage more interesting and captivating, the story arch around the College has finally gotten me glued to the volume.
I do enjoy the seemingly philosophical moments that pop here and there throughout the volume; yet, I would like to see more of Chise and Elias interacting with one another (I feel this College arch has been stealing the spotlight from the bride and magus, but I do understand its importance in drawing this fantasy world even if sometimes it seems to drag on and on forever).

Title: The Complete Maus
Author: Art Spiegelman
My Review:
I was expecting it to be quite a heavy read. Nonetheless, Spiegelman's unique style made it more than just a read: I was tremendously disturbed and terrified, bonded emotionally with the characters and their story and saw the Holocaust through the eyes of a survivor in such vivid lights this was the closest I have ever been to fully understanding what those who've been through it felt.
Maus is not a mere historic fiction comic, it's a masterpiece through which memories of the past live on as a cry for further generations to never forget.

Title: A Relíquia
Author: Eça de Queirós
My Review:
A Relíquia é mais um dos livros onde Eça de Queirós faz uma subtil critica social através de personagens e situações cómicas.
O livro principia num tom extremamente hilariante, onde a personagem principal (e narrador do livro) faz uma apresentação de si próprio ao mesmo tempo que descreve o meio social que o rodeia, quer do ponto de vista conservativo e religioso, quer do de fanfarrão que planeia artimanhas para manter a sua dupla vida de menino rico educado e conservador; deste segundo ponto de vista parte um dos mais interessantes enredos do livro: Teodorico (a personagem principal) inventa as mais diversas artimanhas para parecer, aos olhos da tia, o mais conservador e religioso português da época enquanto aproveita o melhor da vida.
Apesar do início cómico e cativante, onde Teodorico descrever as suas artimanhas, a segunda metade do livro torna-se mais descritiva e adquire um ritmo mais lento o que tornou a sua leitura um tanto pesarosa.
No entanto, a parte final do livro retornou ao estilo cómico e leve com que me apaixonei pelo livro nas suas primeiras páginas, tornando A Relíquia um livro que recomendo avidamente!

Title: The Hobbit (The Lord of the Rings, #0)
Author: J.R.R. Tolkien
Additional Authors: Douglas A. Anderson, Michael Hague, Jemima Catlin
My Review:
I was 7 when my dad began to read me The Hobbit as a bedtime story. I remeber being reluctant about it at first - why in the world would I want to know the story of a scary dragon? He told me to close my eyes and imagine a hole in the ground where a hobbit lived. I got so intrigued by what a hobbit was that I forced him to read as much as he could each night, and when I noticed the book had ended.
The Hobbit is a success in fantasy books, it certainly pushes the reader into Middle-Earth and breaks your heart when you're forced to finish the last page.
And the best thing about The Hobbit?
It has more to it than you could ever imagine.
